 &gt;From:  Bob Braden &lt;braden@edu.isi.venera&gt;
 &gt;Subject: re: reservered names
 &gt;Date:  Thu, 9 Apr 87 08:27:58 PST

 &gt;Dennis,

 &gt;   When our English friends chose to adopt a name ordering reversed from
 &gt;   the (already decided) US standard, they also took on the task of

Fallacy 1.   The NRS choice was made in parallel with the US one.
The original syntax was different too (underscore, not dot).
Some of us presented the US work, and suggested alignment.
We won on the syntax, and lost on the order.   Sigh.

 &gt;   munging names at the boundary.  I don;t think there is any reason in
 &gt;   principle why they can't reverse names at places like UCL that are in
 &gt;   both worlds.

Fallacy 2.   They can and they do.

 &gt;   I suspect that if we dig into it, we will find that
 &gt;   their "problem" is a design/implementation(?) deficiency in MMDF...
 &gt;   e.g., it does not know what channel a message came in on, when it
 &gt;   chooses an output channel.
 &gt;
 &gt;   If they have a problem, they need to fix it.


Fallacy 3.  This is not a design problem.   There is a detailed
note considering the problems of mapping.  (mailgroup note 15
- mapping between RFC 822 and JNT Mail).  I can send you a
copy if you wish.   There  are a number of tradeoffs you can
make at the mapping point.   The "theoretically correct"
mapping has a lot of difficulties with real users.   The
approach I chose for MMDF was conscious.   The gateway can
deal with potentially palindromic names (uk.isi.edu), but it
must be able to access the name (e.g. thru a Domain Nameserver).
Genuinely palindromic cases (Denis's example) must be resolved
one way or the other (i.e. you lose).

 &gt;
 &gt;   Bob Braden
 &gt;
 &gt;

Steve

